Phase II: User Requirements and Application Specifications

#1. Chosen Development Model
Agile Development Model
Justification:
The Agile model was selected because it allows flexibility and continuous improvement throughout the development process. 
Since the Smart Parking Navigator project may evolve based on testing and user feedback, Agile enables the team to adapt quickly. 
It also supports teamwork through regular updates, short development cycles (sprints), and ongoing testing, making it ideal for this type of application.

#2. User Requirements 
As a driver, I want to search for parking near my location so that I can save time.
As a user, I want to view parking spaces on a map so that I can easily choose the closest one.
As a driver, I want to enter a specific location so that I can find parking in another area.
As a user, I want the interface to be simple so that I can use it without confusion.
As a user, I want real-time parking availability so that I can rely on accurate data.
As a driver, I want to see details about each parking space so that I can decide where to park.
As a user, I want the system to load quickly so that I don’t waste time waiting.
As a user, I want to use the app on my phone so that I can access it while driving.
As a user, I want error messages when something goes wrong so that I understand what to do.
As a user, I want my location detected automatically so that I don’t need to type it manually.

